Barplots

Distribution of one categorical variable

When working with a qualitative variable (one in which the data falls into many different categories), the first plot you will likely make is a barplot. This will show how many of each category there are for that particular categorical variable.

Recall the bechdel data frame that was introduced earlier in the course from the fivethirtyeight R package. We will load into the environment here.

library(fivethirtyeight)
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
data(bechdel)

Suppose we are interested in analyzing the distribution of the clean_test variable.

Observe and reflect on the The Bechdel Test Over Time image in the article The Dollar-And-Cents Case Against Hollywoods Exclusion of Women (https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/the-dollar-and-cents-case-against-hollywoods-exclusion-of-women/). You can use this to get a better idea as to what the categories of clean_test represent.

To assist with the plotting, the clean_test variable has been converted to a factor with levels set corresponding to the order given in the plot in the article.

# Convert to factor
bechdel$clean_test <- factor(bechdel$clean_test, ordered = TRUE,
    levels = c("nowomen", "notalk", "men", "dubious", "ok"))

Instructions

  • Produce an appropriate plot looking at the distribution of clean_test in the bechdel data frame.
# Produce an appropriate plot by filling in the entries correctly (and removing the "#" commenting out the following lines).
ggplot(data = bechdel,
       mapping = aes( x = clean_test)) +
  geom_bar()

Distribution of another categorical variable

The plot in the previous exercise is a little deceiving since it appears that ok stands above the other categories. There is a different variable in bechdel that better shows whether a movie passed or failed the Bechdel test.

Instructions

  • Use the glimpse function on bechdel to identify this more appropriate variable. (Recall that you can test code in the R Console first, then enter it into your script when you are happy with it.)
  • Produce a barplot of this variable and also fill based on the different values of the variable.
# Identify the variable that gives pass/fail of the Bechdel test
# library( )

# at first factoring pass and fail
bechdel$binary <- factor(bechdel$binary, ordered = TRUE,
    levels = c("PASS","FAIL"))

# Produce an appropriate plot by filling in the entries correctly
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = bechdel,
        mapping = aes( x = binary, fill = binary)) +
                geom_bar()

Movies over time

The Bechdel Test Over Time image in the article The Dollar-And-Cents Case Against Hollywoods Exclusion of Women breaks down the distribution of clean_test across five year intervals from 1970 to 2014 (1970-74, 1975-79, etc.). Technically, the last interval only contains four years: 2010-13.

We will start by adding a variable five_year to the dataset that will break down the data into the five year intervals mentioned above. Note: these intervals are denoted by the year at the start of the interval.

bechdel <- bechdel %>%
  mutate(five_year = 1970+5*floor((year-1970)/5)) %>%
  mutate(five_year = factor(as.character(five_year),ordered = TRUE, levels = c("1970", "1975", "1980", "1985", "1990","1995","2000","2005","2010")))

Instructions

  • Produce a barplot showing the counts of the number of movies where the years are grouped into the 5 year increments stored in five_year.
ggplot(data = bechdel, mapping = aes(x = year, fill = five_year)) +
        geom_bar() +
        facet_wrap(~five_year)

Bechdel pass/fail over time (stacked)

We can now look at the relationship of movies passing or failing the Bechdel test based on the five_year time periods. In other words, we will be painting the bars you created in the previous exercise proportionally based on the number that FAIL or PASS.

Instructions:

  • Produce a barplot showing the counts of the number of movies in each of the different five_year increments filled according to the levels of binary.
ggplot(data = bechdel, mapping = aes(x = five_year, fill = binary)) +
        geom_bar()

Bechdel pass/fail over time (side-by-side)

We can also shift the bars next to each other instead of being stacked while still being based on the number that FAIL or PASS.

Instructions:

  • Produce a barplot showing the counts of the number of movies in each of the different five_year increments filled according to the levels of binary, but use position = "dodge" instead.
ggplot(data = bechdel, mapping = aes(x = year, fill = five_year)) +
        geom_bar(position = "dodge")

Bechdel pass/fail over time (faceted)

We can also create separate plots for FAIL and PASS using the concept of small multiples.

Instructions:

  • Produce a faceted barplot showing the counts of the number of movies in each of the different five_year increments filled according to the levels of binary, but faceted based on the values of binary to create two different plots on top of each other.
ggplot(data = bechdel, mapping = aes(x = binary, fill = five_year)) +
        geom_bar(color = "white") + 
        facet_wrap(~ binary)

Bechdel pass/fail over time (proportional height)

Each of the last three plots have the common problem that raw counts are shown instead of the proportion of FAIL versus PASS for each five_year increment. While there are circumstances where raw counts make sense, this Bechdel test example leads us to want to explore the percentages of FAIL versus PASS instead.

Instructions:

  • Use position = fill as an argument to geom_bar to create a barplot in the spirit of The Bechdel Test Over Time image in the article The Dollar-And-Cents Case Against Hollywoods Exclusion of Women (https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/the-dollar-and-cents-case-against-hollywoods-exclusion-of-women/).
# creating a variable which calculates the percentage for Y-axis
ggplot(data = bechdel, mapping = aes(x = five_year, fill = binary)) +
        geom_bar(aes(y = (..count..)/sum(..count..)), color = "white") +
        scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)

Showing off

We can actually produce a plot pretty close to the The Bechdel Test Over Time plot by using position = fill and specifying the colors wed like to use instead of the defaults.

The default colors are shown in the plot already loaded for you. As you write the code to create the plot, carefully pull apart how the different elements of the plot match with the Grammar of Graphics theory.

We could continue to tweak the plot to make it look more and more like the actual published plot using nothing but ggplot code. This is one of the great powers of R: its customizability and portability make creating professional-style graphics interactive, fun, and REPRODUCIBLE!

Instructions:

  • After writing the code to produce a stacked barplot of the fractions based on the clean_test variable (with five_year on the horizontal axis and fraction on the vertical axis)
  • Add in this code to color the bars appropriately. (Remember to use the R Console as your sandbox for testing.) scale_fill_manual(values = c("#FF2603", "#FF937F", "#FEC9C3", "#6AB4DA", "#018ED5"))
# Add these lines at the end of your ggplot code
# These will color the bars in the same colors as the FiveThirtyEight plot
# (Note the placement of the + here to be added on to your code.)
#                                    +
# scale_fill_manual(values = c("#FF2603", "#FF937F", "#FEC9C3", "#6AB4DA", "#018ED5"))  
ggplot(data = bechdel, mapping = aes(x = five_year, fill = binary)) +
        geom_bar(aes(y = (..count..)/sum(..count..)), color = "white") +
        scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
        scale_fill_manual(values = c("#FF2603", "#FF937F", "#FEC9C3", "#6AB4DA", "#018ED5"))

Fixing an inappropriate plot for one variable

When one doesnt properly use the correct plot based on the type of variables, some pretty strange plots can be produced. These plots are hard to interpret and often extremely ineffective at telling a story about the data. This exercise and the ones that follow will have you examine why a plot is incorrect and/or fix incorrect code to make a more appropriate plot.

Read over the 2014 article from FiveThirtyEight.com entitled The Economic Guide To Picking A College Major (https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/the-economic-guide-to-picking-a-college-major/). You can find the data corresponding to the story as college_all_ages in the fivethirtyeight R package. We are interested in looking at the distribution of the unemployment_rate variable in this college_all_ages data frame.

Instructions:

  • Fix the code given to produce an appropriate plot looking at how unemployment_rate varies in the college_all_ages data frame.
  • Make sure to also use the color = white argument to better clarify your plot.
library(fivethirtyeight)
ggplot(data = college_all_ages, mapping = aes(x = unemployment_rate)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "white")

## What happened here?

We now shift our data set of interest to the flying data frame in the fivethirtyeight package. First, read the relevant 2014 article on FiveThirtyEight.com (https://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/airplane-etiquette-recline-seat/). Next, carefully read over the documentation for flying via ?fivethirtyeight::flying as well before you begin this problem to better understand what the variables represent. Note here that we use na.omit(flying) instead of flying to remove all of the rows with missing values in the data frame before plotting.

cleanedFlying <- na.omit(flying)
ggplot(data = cleanedFlying, aes(x=age, y= recline_rude))+geom_point()

The plot that is given is not an appropriate plot for looking at the relationship between age and recline_rude. What would be the more appropriate plot?

Possible Answers: D (as age as well as recline_rude are both kind of categorical variables so its better to use stacked barplot. I guess, it might be even best choice than that of faceted histogram although it also quite looks convincing.)
